<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="20997">
<taxonomicName authority="Verrill, 1873" authorityName="Verrill" authorityYear="1873" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Hydroides" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hydroides dianthus" order="Sabellida" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="dianthus">Hydroides dianthus (Verrill, 1873)</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="20997">Notes</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="20997">
Species complex. 
<taxonomicName class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Hydroides" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hydroides dianthus" order="Sabellida" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="dianthus">Hydroides dianthus</taxonomicName>
was originally described from Connecticut and long believed to be non-native in the Mediterranean (
<bibRefCitation author="Zibrowius, H" journalOrPublisher="Rapport et Proces-Verbaux des Reunions de la Commission Internationale pour l'Exploration Scientifique de la Mer Mediterranee" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" pagination="683 - 686" title="Remarques sur trois especes de Serpulidae acclimatees en Mediterranee: Hydroidesdianthus (Verrill, 1873), Hydroidesdirampha Moerch, 1863, et Hydroideselegans (Haswell, 1883)" volume="21" year="1973">Zibrowius 1973b</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Zenetos, Argyro" journalOrPublisher="Estuarine, Coastal and Shelf Science" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" pagination="171 - 187" title="Uncertainties and validation of alien species catalogues: The Mediterranean as an example" volume="191" year="2017">Zenetos et al. 2017</bibRefCitation>
). A recent study by 
<bibRefCitation author="Sun, Yanan" journalOrPublisher="Marine Biology" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" title="A global invader or a complex of regionally distributed species? Clarifying the status of an invasive calcareous tubeworm Hydroidesdianthus (Verrill, 1873) (Polychaeta: Serpulidae) using DNA barcoding" volume="164" year="2017">Sun et al. (2017)</bibRefCitation>
shows, however, that 
<taxonomicName class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Hydroides" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hydroides dianthus" order="Sabellida" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="dianthus">Hydroides dianthus</taxonomicName>
could originate from the Mediterranean, as the species shows the highest genetic diversity in the Mediterranean (nine out of ten haplotypes present, as opposed to only two haplotypes in the USA). The authors recovered also a putative cryptic species, 
<taxonomicName class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Hydroides" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hydroides dianthus" order="Sabellida" pageId="0" pageNumber="20997" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="dianthus">Hydroides cf. dianthus</taxonomicName>
, probably originating from the Gulf of Mexico and apparently recently introduced to the Black Sea.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
